description: From Middle English middes, midst, myddest (“middle”), from Old English midde, reshaped in Middle English phrases like in middes (“in the middle”) by analogy with adverbs in -(e)s; also compare Old English on middan, tōmiddes. Forms in -(e)st are probably due to influence of superlatives.

entries.meaning: (often literary) A place in the middle of something; may be used of a literal or metaphorical location.
(rare) Among, in the middle of; amid.
